{{italic title}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}} [[File:Berlin-Jerusalem DVD cover.jpg|thumb|right|DVD cover]] '''''Berlin-Jerusalem''''' (Hebrew: '''ברלין ירושלים''', tr. ''Berlin Yerushalayim'') is an 89-minute 1989 British-Dutch-French-Israeli-Italian English-, French-, German-, and Hebrew-language independent underground dramatic historical experimental art film directed by [[Amos Gitai]].
==Synopsis== The film tells the story of two women in the 1930s. The first, [[Else Lasker-Schüler]] ([[Lisa Kreuzer]]), a German expressionist poet, observes the rise of Nazism in Berlin before leaving for Jerusalem. The second, the Russian [[Manya Shochat]] ([[Rivka Neumann]]), called Tania in the film, settles in a community in Israel.
==Production== The film was produced by {{ill|Marek Rozenbaum|he|מרק רוזנבאום|pl}}, includes the artistic contributions of [[Pina Bausch]] and was inspired by the paintings of [[George Grosz]], was financed by [[RAI]], [[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting]], [[La Sept]], [[Film4 Productions]], the [[National Center of Cinematography and the moving image|National Center of Cinematography and the Moving Image]], and {{ill|Le Volcan|fr|Le Volcan (salle)|pl|Wulkan (Hawr)|pt|Centro Cultural Le Havre|tr|Le Havre Kültür Merkezi}}, was distributed by [[Facets Multi-Media]], was shot by [[Henri Alekan]] and [[Nurith Aviv]], was edited by {{ill|Marco Melani|it}}, [[Antoine Bonfanti]], {{ill|Michel Klochendler|fr}}, and {{ill|Luc Barnier|de|Luc Barnier|fr|Luc Barnier|pt}}, was cast by {{ill|Levia Hon|he|לביאה הון}}, and also stars ''inter alia'' [[Markus Stockhausen]] (who also composed the score together with {{ill|Simon Stockhausen|de}}), [[Vernon Dobtcheff]], [[Veronica Lazăr]], [[Bernard Eisenschitz]], {{ill|Yossi Graber|he|יוסי גרבר}}, [[Juliano Mer-Khamis]], [[Mark Ivanir]], [[Keren Mor]], {{ill|Ori Levy|he|אורי לוי (שחקן)}}, and {{ill|Ohad Shahar|he|אוהד שחר|ja|オーハド・シャハー}}.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kronish|first1=Amy W.|last2=Safirman|first2=Costel|date=May 2003|title=Israeli Film: A Reference Guide|url=https://www.abc-clio.com/product.aspx?pc=D1266C|location=Westport, Connecticut and London|publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]]’s [[Greenwood Publishing Group]] and Praeger Publishers|pages=32–33|isbn=9780313321443|series=Reference Guides to the World’s Cinema, Series Editor: Prof. Dr. Pierre L. Horn|oclc=845524002|accessdate=30 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{ill|Gross, Natan|he|נתן גרוס|pl|Natan Gross}}. {{cite book|date=1991|script-title=he:'''הסרט העברי – פרקים בתולדות הראינוע והקולנוע בישראל: 1896–1991'''|trans-title=The Hebrew Film – Chapters in the Annals of Silent and Sound Cinema in Israel: 1896–1991|page=446|location=Jerusalem|language=Hebrew|publisher=Natan and {{ill|Yaacov Gross|he|יעקב גרוס|}}|oclc=27221790|url=https://google.com/books?id=muosAAAAIAAJ|accessdate=30 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Handler|first=Dr. Deborah|script-title=he:ייצוגה של ירושלים בקולנוע הישראלי|trans-title=Representations of Jerusalem in Israeli Cinema|date=2004|url=https://www.orot.ac.il/sites/default/files/tallelei-orot/11-18.pdf|language=Hebrew|work=Tallelei Orot'', Volume 11''|location=Elkana|access-date=30 September 2018|publisher={{ill|Orot Israel College of Education|he|מכללת אורות ישראל}}|page=281}}</ref><ref>''Berlin-Jerusalem''. In: {{cite book|title=A Guide to Films Featured in the Jewish Film Festival|last1=Kaufman|first=Deborah|last2=Plotkin|first2=Janis|last3=Orenstein|first3=Rena, eds.|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=BdQqAQAAIAAJ|date=1991|publisher=Jewish Film Festival|location=Berkeley, California|access-date=30 September 2018|oclc=25527469|page=15}} Reprinted in: {{cite book|title=Independent Jewish Film: A Resource Guide|last1=Plotkin|first=Janis|last2=Libresco|first2=Caroline|last3=Feiger|first3=Josh, eds.|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=mPFkAAAAMAAJ|date=1996|publisher=[[San Francisco Jewish Film Festival]]|location=San Francisco, California|access-date=30 September 2018|oclc=36119531|page=46|isbn=9780965068802|edition=3rd.}}</ref>
==Reception== [[File:Amos portrait 1.jpg|thumb|Amos Gitai (April 2011)]] The film was screened at the [[46th Venice International Film Festival]] during September 1989 (where it won several awards and was nominated for the [[Golden Lion]]), at the 1990 [[International Istanbul Film Festival]] (where it also won several awards), at the [[1989 Toronto International Film Festival]] on 13 September 1989, and at the [[42nd Berlin International Film Festival]] on 22 February 1992. The journalist Daniel Warth has opined that “although the film is minimalistic, it is nonetheless ravishing.”<ref>{{cite news|last=Warth|first=Daniel|script-title=he:תפיסות מנוגדות|trans-title=Conflicting Visions|date=14 December 1990|url=http://idea.cinema.co.il/ideawebinter/multimedia_11/0165/01650176.pdf|language=Hebrew|work=[[Ha'ir|Ha’ir]]|location=Tel Aviv-Yafo|access-date=30 September 2018|publisher=Haaretz Group’s Schocken Group}}</ref> The film was released in Israel, where it was released to the general public by {{ill|Nurith Shani|he|נורית שני}}’s {{ill|Shani Films|he|לב (רשת בתי קולנוע)}} and the [[Tel Aviv Cinematheque]] on 7 December 1990 (the film was released on 14 March 1990 in France and on 13 December 1991 in the Neherlands), together with ''Esther'' (1986) as part of a DVD boxset in 2005.<ref>{{cite AV media|date=2005|script-title=he:'''ברלין ירושלים'''|trans-title=Berlin-Jerusalem|people=Gitai, Prof. Dr. Amos|location=Ramat HaSharon|publisher=[[NMC Music]]’s Globus United King Films|language=Hebrew|format=DVD|accessdate=30 September 2018|url=http://israel-music.com/various/berlin_jerusalem|OCLC=920667873}}</ref>
