{{for|♂, ♀ etc.|Gender symbol}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}} [[File:Barris Marilyn Monroe.jpg|thumb|According to the [[BBC]], "[[Marilyn Monroe]] is perhaps Hollywood's most enduring sex symbol".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/p00w1zk0/Witness_The_Death_of_Marilyn_Monroe/|title=BBC World Service - Witness, The Death of Marilyn Monroe|work=BBC|accessdate=30 December 2014}}</ref>]]
A [[sex symbol]] is a [[celebrity]] of either sex, typically an [[actor]] or [[actress]], [[musician]], [[supermodel]], [[teen idol]], [[sports star]], or even a [[politician]], noted for being widely regarded as [[Sexual attraction|sexually attractive]]. The term was first used in the mid-1950s in relation to the popularity of certain film stars, including [[Marilyn Monroe]], [[Brigitte Bardot]], [[Marlon Brando]], and [[Raquel Welch]].<ref name=Flexner>{{cite book |title=Speaking freely: a guided tour of American English from Plymouth Rock to Silicon Valley |first=Stuart Berg |last=Flexner |author-link=Stuart Berg Flexner |first2=Anne H. |last2=Soukhanov |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |year=1997 |page=373 |isbn=978-0-19-510692-3 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=FlANAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA373}}</ref>
