[[File:Civil_Flag_of_Serbia.svg|thumb|Civil [[Flag of Serbia]].]] The '''[[national colours]] of [[Serbia]]''' are red, blue and white,<ref>{{cite book|title=The Journal of the Orders & Medals Research Society of Great Britain|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W0BmAAAAMAAJ|year=1969|publisher=Orders and Medals Research Society|page=207}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Chronicles|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_lMIAQAAMAAJ|year=1994|publisher=Rockford Institute|page=39}}</ref><ref name="ThomasMikulan2006">{{cite book|author1=Nigel Thomas|author2=Krunoslav Mikulan|title=The Yugoslav Wars (2): Bosnia, Kosovo and Macedonia 1992 - 2001|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a7cOQ9Nch2AC&pg=PA58|year=2006|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=978-1-84176-964-6|page=58}}</ref> the [[Flag of Serbia]] being commonly called ''trobojka'' (the [[tricolour (flag)|tricolour]]).<ref name="armije1974">{{cite book|author=Vojni muzej Jugoslovenske marodne armije|title=Vesnik|volume=19-20|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HAMgAAAAMAAJ|year=1974|quote=Srpska trobojka: crveno-plavo-belo}}</ref> This flag was adopted in 1835.<ref name="Јанковић2008">{{cite book|author=Зорица Јанковић|title=Цару на диван: сусрети српских владара и турских султана|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EQYWAQAAMAAJ|year=2008|publisher="Београд|quote=ферманом је одређена: црвено-плаво-бела тробојка, са водоравно поређаним бојама.}}</ref>
