{{Infobox book | name = The Lion of Flanders | title_orig = De Leeuw van Vlaenderen, of de Slag der Gulden Sporen | translator = | image = Leeuwvanvlaenderen.gif | image_size=170px | caption = The [[title page]] of the 1838 first edition | author = [[Hendrik Conscience]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = [[Belgium]] | language = [[Dutch language|Dutch]] | series = | subject = [[War novel|War]], [[Romance novel|Romance]] | genre = [[Historical fiction]] | publisher = L.J. de Cort ([[Antwerp]]) | release_date = 1838 | english_pub_date = 1855 | media_type = | pages = | isbn = | dewey = 839.3 | congress = | oclc = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''The Lion of Flanders, or the Battle of the Golden Spurs''''' ({{lang-nl|'''De Leeuw van Vlaenderen, of de Slag der Gulden Sporen'''}}<!--The Dutch spelling in archaic but correct-->) is a major [[novel]] first published in 1838 by the [[Belgium|Belgian]] writer [[Hendrik Conscience]] (1812–83). An early example of the [[historical fiction]] genre, the ''Lion of Flanders'' focuses on the medieval [[Franco-Flemish War]] and the [[Battle of the Golden Spurs]] of 1302 in particular. It is written in Conscience's typical stylistic [[romanticism]] and has been described as the "Flemish national epic".{{sfn|Hermann|2016|p=59}}
Unusually for its time, the work was written in Dutch and it is considered one of the founding texts of [[Flemish literature]]. This gave it an enduring political influence within the [[Flemish Movement]] and its contemporary success also confirmed Conscience's reputation as a novelist.
== Background == [[Hendrik Conscience]] was born in the Flemish city of [[Antwerp]] into a mixed French-Flemish family in 1812. Conscience was brought up bilingual, speaking both [[French language|French]] and [[Dutch language|Dutch]].{{sfn|Hermans|2014|p=162}} After briefly working as a teacher, he participated in the [[Belgian Revolution]] in 1830 and later served in the Belgian army during the [[Ten Days' Campaign]] of 1831, inspired by the contemporary ideology of [[romantic nationalism]]. He left the army in 1836 and moved to the [[Campine (region)|Kempen region]] where he began to pursue a literary career.
[[File:Nicaise de Keyser02.jpg|thumb|left|''De Slag der Gulden Sporen'' (1836) by [[Nicaise de Keyser]] may have served as an inspiration for the book{{sfn|Hermann|2016|p=57}}]] Conscience worked in the new genre of [[historical fiction]] which had emerged in [[Europe]] around 1800.{{sfn|Literatuurgeschiedenis|b}} His early writing combined his interests in the language and history of [[Flanders]] with [[Romanticism|literary romanticism]]. His first book, ''[[In 't Wonderjaer]]'' (''In the Year of Wonder'') was published in 1837 and explored both themes.{{sfn|EB|online}} It was the first work of historical fiction yet published in Dutch and was set during the ''[[Beeldenstorm]]'' of 1566 and the revolt by [[Calvinism|Calvinists]] of the [[Spanish Netherlands]] against Catholic rule. Conscience was only able to publish the work with the support of friends, including [[Leopold I of Belgium|King Leopold I]].{{sfn|Hermans|2014|p=164}} Though relatively successful, the work made him little money and Conscience began work on a new book.{{sfn|Hermans|2014|p=164}}
The innovative dimension of Conscience's work was his use of Dutch language in his writing. At the time, Belgian [[high culture]] was dominated by French, the established language of the upper classes and state bureaucracy across the country. Though Dutch dialects were commonly spoken in Flanders as a [[vernacular]], their use was considered vulgar by the bourgeoisie and inappropriate in literature. Conscience, however, believed that Dutch provided a more authentic form of expression and preferred to use it, making his works unusual at the time.
== Novel == [[File:HendrikConscience.gif|thumb|upright|Portrait of [[Hendrik Conscience]] as a young man]] In 1838, Conscience published his second book, entitled ''De Leeuw van Vlaenderen, of de Slag der Gulden Sporen''{{efn|The "ae" combination from ''Vlaenderen'' (Flanders) is [[History of Dutch orthography|considered archaic]] in modern Dutch and is replaced by ''Vlaanderen'' in modern editions.}} (''The Lion of Flanders, or the Battle of the Golden Spurs''). The book was set in [[County of Flanders|Medieval Flanders]] and focused on the [[Franco-Flemish War]] (1297–1305). Its centerpiece was the [[Battle of the Golden Spurs|Battle of Kortrik]] of 1302, commonly known as the Battle of the Golden Spurs (''Guldensporenslag''), in which a small Flemish force, made up of local militia, unexpectedly defeated a superior invading force from the [[Kingdom of France]]. In choosing the topic, Conscience may have been inspired by a romantic painting of the battle by the Flemish artist [[Nicaise de Keyser]], unveiled in 1836.{{sfn|Hermann|2016|p=57}} Conscience's work approaches the subject through the romance between Machteld, daughter of [[Robert III, Count of Flanders]] (the eponymous "Lion of Flanders"), and the [[knight]] Adolf van Nieuwlandt. The book famously concludes with a direct injunction to the reader:
{{quote|''Gy Vlaming, die dit boek gelezen hebt, overweeg, by de roemryke daden welke hetzelve bevat, wat Vlaenderen eertyds was – wat het nu is – en nog meer wat het worden zal indien gy de heilige voorbeelden uwer Vaderen vergeet!''
You Fleming, who have read this book, reflect, through the glorious deeds that it recounts, what Flanders once was, what it is now, and even more what it shall become if you forget the sacred examples of your forefathers!{{sfn|Literatuurgeschiedenis|b}} }}
In his foreword to the 1838 edition, Conscience explicitly stated that he intended his book to raise Flemish [[national consciousness]] and patriotism.{{sfn|Hermann|2016|p=59}} Conscience researched the historical events by reading contemporary [[chronicle]]s and his narrative frequently diverged from historical fact, contributed to the mythelogisation of the events as clash between the Flemish and French-speaking invaders.{{sfn|Literatuurgeschiedenis|b}}{{sfn|Hermann|2016|p=59}}
=== Reception === [[File:Kortrijk-Groeningemonument.jpg|thumb|upright|The [[Groeninge Monument]] (1906) in [[Kortrijk]] commemorates the Battle of the Golden Spurs, popularised by Conscience]] The ''[[Encyclopædia Britannica]]'' describes ''De Leeuw'' as a "passionate epic" and compares it to the historical fiction of the Scottish writer [[Walter Scott|Sir Walter Scott]] (1771–1832).{{sfn|EB|online}} With the immense success of the ''De Leeuw van Vlaanderen'' Conscience was widely credited as the man "who taught his people to read" (''leerde zijn volk lezen'') in [[popular culture]].{{sfn|Literatuurgeschiedenis|a}} The work's public success confirmed Conscience's reputation as the leading Flemish novelist of his generation. By the time of his death in 1883, he had written around 100 novels and novellas.{{sfn|Hermans|2014|p=162}}
The publication of ''The Lion'' coincided with the emergence of the [[Flemish Movement]] which supported an increasingly assertive Flemish political identity. As a celebration of Dutch language and Flemish history, the ''Lion'' became popular among ''flamingants'' and contributed to the increasing importance of the Battle of the Golden Spurs in Flemish political memory.{{sfn|Literatuurgeschiedenis|b}} The battle itself had been largely forgotten before Conscience's work but was revived.{{sfn|Hermann|2016|p=58}} Among other things, it inspired the [[flag of Flanders]] and the anthem "[[De Vlaamse Leeuw]]" (1847) by [[Hippoliet Van Peene]].{{sfn|Literatuurgeschiedenis|b}} It has been noted, however, that the increased status of the work in Flemish nationalist consciousness also coincided with a decreasing readership.{{sfn|Willems|2014}} Conscience himself believed that Flemish and Belgian patriotisms were complementary and was himself a [[Belgian nationalism|Belgian nationalist]].{{sfn|Literatuurgeschiedenis|a}}
== Adaptations == ''The Lion of Flanders'' has been the subject of various adaptations. At least nine [[Franco-Belgian comics|comic strip adaptations]] have been produced;{{sfn|Hermann|2016|p=61}} the most celebrated was by [[Bob De Moor]] and was serialised in ''[[Tintin (magazine)|Tintin]]'' after 1949 and published as a single volume in 1952. It was acclaimed as one of his best works.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stripspeciaalzaak.be/Toppers/BelgenTop100/48_LeeuwVlaanderen.htm|title=BelgenTop 50 nr. 48: De Leeuw van Vlaanderen|website=www.stripspeciaalzaak.be}}</ref> Also notable is Karel Biddeloo's loose adaptation of the work in 1984 within the ''[[De Rode Ridder]]'' series, inspired by [[surrealism]].{{sfn|Hermann|2016|p=57}}
The work was also adapted into a film in 1984, directed by the celebrated Flemish writer [[Hugo Claus]], to commemorate the anniversary of Conscience's death. The film was itself adapted into a television series by Claus in 1985.{{sfn|Willems|2014}} The work was a co-production between various private and state groups in Belgium and the Netherlands and, at 80 million [[Belgian franc]]s, was the most expensive film produced in the [[Low Countries]] to date.{{sfn|Willems|2014}} As director, Claus attempted to stick as closely to the original text as possible. The film was a commercial and critical disaster, criticised for excessive romanticism and Flemish nationalist politics.{{sfn|Willems|2014}}
